I"~<h4>Nella said "Love is complated, but web-dev is much more."</h4>
<p>How it works when they are involved in a love hurricane with django, front-end and heroku?</p>

<ul>
  <li>goal to go: build <a href="https://hsiaocy.herokuapp.com/">my online resume</a></li>
  <li>things to have:
    <ol>
      <li>Django - overall web framework</li>
      <li>front-end - <a href="https://freehtml5.co/profile-free-html5-bootstrap-template-for-personal-and-vcard-resume-websites/">a fancy template</a></li>
      <li>heroku - deploy your site</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Items:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Django
    <ul>
      <li><strong>prerequisites</strong>: python3.x, venv and Django pack are already installed</li>
      <li><strong>Create a project</strong>: it contains all the stuff we will mention later, here use “UnchainedDjango” as my project name. Oepn CLI and change directory to “UnchainedDjango/” to create project. Keeping use UnchainedDjango as project name, and you will get a tree like</li>
    </ul>
    <pre class="brush: bash">
     django-admin startproject UnchainedDjango
     cd UnchainedDjango

     .(UnchainedDjango)  &lt;- root dir, "git init" here for heroku deployment
     ├── manage.py       &lt;- our tool script (python3 manage.py [func])
     └── unchaineddjango &lt;- 
         ├── __init__.py
         ├── asgi.py
         ├── settings.py &lt;- site configuratin manager
         ├── urls.py     &lt;- url's boss which manages all sites, import app's site here
         └── wsgi.py
 </pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Create a app</strong>: to generate a folder which points to the site(app). If you want to modify at site, modify here. More detail: <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.0/intro/tutorial01/#creating-the-polls-app">link</a></li>
    </ul>

    <pre class="brush: bash">
     django-admin startapp homepage

     .(UnchainedDjango)  &lt;- root dir, "git init" here for heroku deployment
     ├── manage.py
     ├── unchaineddjango/
     └── hoamepage/
         ├── migrations/
         │	└─__init__.py
         ├── __init__.py
         ├── admin.py
         ├── app.py
         ├── models.py
         ├── tests.py
         ├── urls.py     &lt;- not default created, need to create by myself
         └── views.py   
 </pre>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Summary
	- There’s a bunch of tutorial to guide you to do so, I won’t do that again.
	- Some frequently used commands:
		- django-admin startproject [project_name]
		- django-admin startapp [app_name]: 
		- python3 manage.py runserver: debug at localhost(127.0.0.1:8000), remember to set DEBUG=True at setting.py
	- Here are some frequently used files:
		- UnchainedDjango/manage.py: god tool for master this project
		-</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>- Django provides the completed instruction for beginner, but I already targeted so I skipped those steps.
- You have to modify files: urls.py, setting.py
	- add links in 	
	- DEBUG = False
</code></pre></div></div>

<ol>
  <li>heroku deploy
    <ul>
      <li>You will need three files:
        <ul>
          <li>Procfile
            <ul>
              <li>just create the file named Procfile without any extension</li>
              <li>open Procfile and insert following command:
                <pre class="brush: bash">web: gunicorn --pythonpath mysite mysite.wsgi --log-file - </pre>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>runtime.txt
            <ul>
              <li>insert your python version, e.g. mine is 3.6.5
                <pre class="brush: bash">python-3.6.5</pre>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>requirements.txt
            <ul>
              <li>type at root dir
                <pre class="brush: bash"> pip3 freeze &gt; requirements.txt</pre>
              </li>
              <li>then open “requirements.txt” and insert this package in the file
                <pre class="brush: bash">psycopg2</pre>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>
